commit_message: Initial commit
Add initial project files
Add vim statusline exampleThis is currently rendered with the terminal renderer, and is justna simple proof-of-concept of how vim statuslines can be defined with thenPython API.n
Fix soft separator issue with vim divider segments

Join the fg/bg/attr methods of the renderersThis change joins the fg/bg/attr methods into a single hl method in thenrenderers. This provides the same functionality, and it simplifies thenterminal rendering by being able to join all the attributes into onenescape sequence.nnIt's also a necessary change for the vim renderer, as this renderernneeds to log all the highlighting and create separate highlightingnclasses for every single color and attribute combination. The only waynto do this is to have a single highlighting method.n
Fix default segment attribute value

Create basic vim segment rendererThis commit also includes a basic proof-of-concept demo for creating vimnstatuslines. When creating vim statuslines you basically need to firstncreate the statusline the same way as the terminal demo, use the vimnrenderer and then afterwards loop through the collected highlight groupsnin the vim renderer and write those as vim highlight statements.nnVim obviously needs a ton of wrapper code to make everything worknproperly (separate modes, callbacks, all that stuff) so the current demononly shows some basic statusline highlighting.n
Change wording: separator -> divider
Move vimscript hl statement generation to vim renderer

Improve the Segment class and renderingThe Segment class has been given two new properties: priority andnfiller. The render method has been given a width argument.nnIf the width argument is specified when rendering a segment and thenrendered segments are too wide, segments are dropped in order ofnpriority, with the lowest priority (highest number) being dropped firstnand any segment with priority < 0 is kept, regardless of the specifiednwidth.nnIf the width argument is specified along with one or more fillernsegments, the filler segments will pad the remaining space with spacencharacters until the desired width has been reached.nnThe handling of segment attributes has also been improved by lazilynlooking up the correct attributes in the segment tree when it's beingnrendered.nnFinally, the rendering code itself has been improved a bit with lessncode duplication and much more readable code.n

Create dynamic vim statusline exampleThis example only does a single type of highlighting (normal mode) butndemonstrates nicely how rendering a statusline with Python could work.nThis also utilizes the new width functionality to crop away lessnimportant segment if the window is too small, and do the padding withnPython instead of using vim's split segment.nnSome optimization will probably be necessary, as calling Python for eachnstatusline redraw is quite expensive. A solution could be evaluating thensegments in Python once and then calculating the width and crop away/padnthe segments, and then sending the statusline with unevaluated segmentsnto vim for rendering without calling Python. Only some events (likenCursorHold, InsertEnter/InsertLeave, etc.) would trigger a re-rendernwith Python, a recalculation of the width and cropping/padding.n
Update vim statusline exampleNow the vim statusline example does everything in Python, so the pythonnexample isn't required anymore.n
Simplify filler rendering
Fix issues with terminal renderer

Fix segment paddingThe padding argument has been removed and is now handled automatically.nSegments without dividers are not padded anymore.nnThis was necessary to ensure that segments are rendered correctly whenncropping segments (overriding the padding argument screwed up thenpadding for segments without dividers and without padding).n
Fix vim statusline example
Remove get_hl_statements from vim renderer

Add unicode stuff for Python 2Powerline will probably only be Python 2 in the foreseeable futurenbecause of poor Python 3 support in applications like vim, so thisnsmall change ensures correct unicode behavior in Python 2.n

Rewrite core code to only allow a single-dimensional segment arrayThe segment tree seemed like a good idea at the time, but for the corencode it's probably best to do a single-dimensional array and insteadnhave some duplicated data (common segment attributes). By removing thentree structured segments the code is much simpler to understand and use,nand probably quite a bit faster.nnIf a tree structure is wanted for ease of configuration, it could easilynbe supported in the JSON config files for vim statuslines, and thennletting the vim statusline code flatten the configuration intona single-dimensional array for rendering.n
Ignore empty segments that aren't filler segments

Update vim and terminal examplesThe examples have been moved into their own directory. The vim examplennow uses pyeval() and vim.bindeval() and loads the Python file throughnan import (so it gets compiled) for speed improvements.n

Handle remainder whitespace for filler segmentsWhen more than one filler segment is specified it may sometimes bena remainder when calculating the amount of whitespace. divmod() is usednto retrieve the remainder, which is added as whitespace to the firstnfiller segment.n
Fix issues with the terminal prompt example

Make vim example work with split and inactive windowsThis commit introduces a bunch of changes. Most importantly, it ensuresnthat split windows and inactive windows work as expected. This isnaccomplished with some clever workarounds for vim's statuslinenlimitations.nnVim statuslines evaluated using the %! statusline item are alwaysnevaluated in the buffer context and not in the statusline's ownernwindow's context, and this made the previous implementation show thensame statusline for all windows. The only way to ensure that the correctnstatusline is rendered to the correct window is to walk through allnwindows, and setting the statuslines with a reference to the currentnwindow number every time the current window is changed. This isnaccomplished by a set of BufEnter, BufLeave, etc. autocommands.nnThe Syntastic segment has been temporarily removed due to errors whennreferencing the statusline function before Syntastic has been loaded.n

Improve rendering performanceThis commit almost doubles the segment rendering performance. This isnaccomplished by caching a lot of data like highlighting groups, movingnsome calculations out of loops, and by performing less function callsnoverall.nnWhen a width is specified the main speed improvement comes from avoidingnrendering the raw segments over and over until the statusline is shortnenough. Instead, the raw rendering is stored as a segment property andnthe combined length of all these renderings is used when removingnlow-priority segments instead. This results in a maximum of twonrendering passes.nnSome less pythonic solutions have been chosen some places fornperformance reasons, e.g. joining strings instead of appending andnjoining lists.nnOverall this commit appears to make the performance equal or better thannthe legacy vimscript implementation. Later optimizations (in particularnfinding another method than remove() for removing low-priority segments)nmay make this version of Powerline far superior both in terms ofnfunctionality and performance.n

Improve rendering performanceThis change removes the Segment class as this takes forever to removenfrom the segment array when removing low-priority segments. It hasninstead been replaced by a wrapper function that works the same andnreturns a working dict of all segment properties.nnThe regex substitution bottleneck in the vim example has been fixed bynusing a single-character percent placeholder in vim segments which isnlater replaced with a double percent using str.replace().n

Fix various rendering issuesAnother rendering pass is necessary before calculating the fillernsegment's lengths, because center segments may lose their separatorsnafter removing low-priority segments.nnSome unicode and variable assignment issues has been resolved soneverything renders correctly.n

Cache statusline contents in PythonEach window is now tagged with an UUID and this UUID is used to cachenthe window's statusline contents in the Python VimRenderer in order tonavoid translating the statusline contents to and from a vimdictnunnecessarily.nnRefs #11.n

Cache segment contents after rendering the statuslineNon-current segments used the wrong contents because outdatedninformation was cached (self.segments was repopulated in the render()nmethod which was called *after* the contents was cached). Now thencontents are cached after the parent class' render() method is called sonthe correct information is cached.nnCloses #11.n
Pass the current window as a parameter to the render methodThis change simplifies the code somewhat as the BufLeave, etc. autocmdsnaren't required anymore.n

Restructure segment rendering methodsTheme.get_segments() is now a generator which returns segment copies,nand it no longer handles segment content replacement.nnRenderer.render() accepts a theme and a segments parameter in order tonoverride the default actions (calling self.get_theme() andnself.get_segments()). This is necessary to be able to cache themes andnsegment contents somewhere else and provide the cached data to thenrender method. The render method now also handles removing excludednsegments, which was previously handled in Theme.get_segments().nnFinally, VimRenderer.render() caches all theme and segment data andnprovides this data to the renderer for non-current windows.nnCloses #12.n

Purge out :echoe`:echoe` is unstable: unless it is already in `:try`u00e2u0080u00a6`:catch` blocknyou never know for sure whether or not it will break execution.nThus the only valid use for `:echoe` isnntrynechoe 'Msg'nendtryn: rough equivalent to `:throw` (throws, but with different message).nAs this is probably not the thing you want to donI changed it to use `:echomsg`.n

Add virtcol parameter for col_current segmentThe virtual column number is also default. I doubt anybody here evernwanted to see byte offset. When it comes to a questions like alignment,nforced text width and so on only virtual columns matter. It would bengood to optionally take concealed characters into account, but vim doesnnot provide a way to do so (well, except recent screencol() added solelynfor testing which would be hard, but not impossible, to adapt to suchnneeds).nnCloses #25.n

Add file_vcs_status segment, using powerline.lib.vcs instead of fugitiveUsing pure-python implementation allows to use the same code in thenterminal segments (not implemented currently). It also should be moreneffective. Git module is able to use pygit2 instead of command-line gitnwhich is much faster. Mercurial module assumes that mercurial is alwaysnaccessible as a python module.nnCode for repository (not file) status is untested. It exists solely fornterminal segments.nnCloses #26.n

Highlight VCS flags differentlyM flag is highlighted in yellow, A flag is highlighted in green,nother flags are highlighted in red. This also corresponds with thenhighlighting in the output of `git status`.nnWhitespace is also trimmed from the flags as the columns don't matternmuch in vim statuslines, and empty columns only introduce whitespacenthat looks like a bug.n

Recreate git.Repository() on each callIt appears that pygit2 has similar to mercurialu00e2u0080u0099s issue with statusesn(they are not updated) and needs to be regenerated on each call as well.nImplies to index statuses only though, that is why I used to thinknpygit2 does not have this problem.n

Update terminal renderer output depending on shellBash and zsh have different ways of escaping colors in the prompt, thisnupdate checks the $SHELL environment variable and uses the correctnescape sequence for the current shell.nnA known issue with this method is that $SHELL doesn't get updated whennswitching shells (i.e. if you're running /bin/bash when you're in a zshnshell) so in rare cases rendering errors may occur. A workaround whichnis much slower is to parse the output of `ps -p $$` which always returnsnthe current shell.n

Refactor segment renderingThis commit introduces the following changes to themes and segmentnrendering:nn- Spacer segments are now regular string/function type segments withn  width: auto in the themes.n- The rjust/ljust properties have been replaced by the widthn  option combined with a new align option.n- Renderer._render_segments() is now a generator which renders eachn  segment separately, and assigns the rendered contents ton  _rendered_hl and _rendered_raw in the segment dict.n- Renderer.render() returns the segments by joining the _rendered_hln  values for each segment.n- Spacer segment widths are calculated in the render() method, andn  assigned to _space_left and _space_right in the segment dict.n  These spaces are then applied in Renderer._render_segments().n- All space characters are converted to no-break spaces (U+00A0) in then  _rendered_hl property.nnRefs #113.nRefs #154.n

Replace spaces *before* highlighting contentsThe previous change obviously didn't work for renderers like the Pangonmarkup renderer since the highlighting code uses regular spaces and notnno-break spaces. Now spaces are replaced in the contents and dividersnonly, and it's done before highlighting the segment so the addednhighlighting code stays untouched.nnRefs #113.n

Fix statusline highlighting after leaving a cmdwinBecause vim doesn't trigger any autocmds after leaving a cmdwin thenstatusline in the window the user returned to from the cmdwin would benhighlighted as non-current even if it should have been current.nnThis issue is resolved by storing the last current window ID in a scriptnvariable, and when leaving the cmdwin we show the last current window asncurrent instead of detecting it after the WinEnter autocmd has beenntriggered (which doesn't happen after leaving a cmdwin).nnCloses #184.n

And, the ``install`` command can handle directory creation and file installation in the same command which cuts a great deal of unnecessary commands out.rnrnAlso, remember, msg2s in the package function will be printed during the making of the package, not during the installation. And, the ``install`` command can handle directory creation and file installation in the same command which cuts a great deal of unnecessary commands out.rnrnAlso, remember, ``msg2`` in the package function will be printed during the making of the package, not during the installation. Fix git branch name sometimes getting stuck with inotifyIf you try to checkout the already current branch in git, git createsnHEAD.lock and renames it to HEAD. This causes the inode of HEAD tonchange and so the inotify file watcher stops tracking HEAD.nnThe fix is to re-create the inotify watch when the file attributesnchange. This is a bit of a performance penalty as most of the time thenattribute changes are simple last modified time/size changes, but sinceninotify provides no way to know specifically when the inode has changed,nthis is the best we can do.n

tmux: Change session block color if prefix pressedThis modification to the tmux powerline binding allows the user toneasily identify when the prefix has been sent. When the prefix hasnbeen sent, the session block changes from white to blue (matching thencolor of the active window). This is accomplished using the conditionalnfunctionality of tmux format strings and the 'client_prefix' formatnvariable. Unfortunately, the tmux parser fails to properly parse outncomma-separated format strings inside a format conditional, so thosenhave been split out into individual segments as well. Attempting tonre-combine the formats inside the conditionals will break this feature.n

tmux: Colorize the last active window FGUse a feature of tmux v1.8+ to change the FG color of the last activenwindow to blue. This uses the foo-{attr,bg,fg} format, which isndeprecated (although still available) starting with tmux v1.9 in favornof the corresponding foo-style variable. However, tmux v1.9 is not yetnubiquitous enough to move to the foo-style variables. For example, thenlatest Ubuntu LTS (14.04) only has tmux v1.8 available in itsnrepositories, so the foo-{attr,bg,fg} variables prove to be moren'compatible' for now.nnFor future reference, here is the modification that should be made oncentmux v1.8 is deemed old enough to drop support for (or whenever thendeprecated foo-{attr,bg,fg} variables go away in the latest version ofntmux):nn-set -g window-status-last-fg colour31n+set -g window-status-last-style fg=colour31nnIt might be appropriate to add version checking around some of thesentypes of options for maximum compatibility, but my initial attempt tonexplore version checking in the tmux config file got extremely messy inna hurry.n

tmux: Enhance version checking for tmuxtmux configuration has become very fragmented between versions due to ancombination of new features and deprecation of older options. As such,nversion checking for tmux became a requirement to allow maximumnfunctionality along with version-appropriate configuration. However,nwrapping nearly every line with `if-shell` is tedious and becomesnvirtually unreadable.nnThis enhancement to tmux version-checking creates a logicalnconfiguration file structure that reflects the development of tmux. Asnadditional configurations are added and tmux development continues, thisnstructure can be leveraged appropriately and extended as needed.nnRather than having multiple `if-shell` checks for the same version, eachnversion or version group with specific requirements can be checked onlynonce. This leads to simpler and fewer `if-shell` version checks. It alsonreduces the ambiguity introduced by complex `if-shell` commands thatninclude an 'else' conditional.nnA caveat to adding this enhancement is the additional requirement of thenend user to add a tmux variable definition (`POWERLINE_BINDINGS_DIR`) tonhis/her `~/.tmux.conf` file. For existing tmux users leveragingnpowerline, this may prove to be a slight one-time nuisance immediatelynafter upgrading. Without this definition, there is no way to determinenthe location of the additional tmux powerline config files that havenbeen added with this enhancement. The docs have also been updated innthis commit to reflect this initial configuration requirement change.nAlso added are some additional troubleshooting notes that point tondefinition of this variable as a potential issue. Powerline willncontinue to work without the definition of `POWERLINE_BINDINGS_DIR`, butnsome of the functionality will be reduced and the appearance incompleten(i.e. colors).nnUltimately, the caveat above is a small price to pay in exchange for anframework that can be leveraged for proper version-appropriatenconfiguration of tmux going forward.n

Unify importsNow imports follow the following structure:nn1. __future__ line: exactly one line allowed:nnfrom __future__ import (unicode_literals, division, absolute_import, print_function)nn   (powerline.shell is the only exception due to problems with argparse).n2. Standard python library imports in a form `import X`.n3. Standard python library imports in a form `from X import Y`.n4. and 5. 2. and 3. for third-party (non-python and non-powerline imports).n6. 3. for powerline non-test imports.n7. and 8. 2. and 3. for powerline testing module imports.nnEach list entry is separated by exactly one newline from another import. Ifnthere is module docstring it goes between `# vim:` comment and `__future__`nimport. So the structure containing all items is the following:nn#!/usr/bin/env pythonn# vim:fileencoding=utf-8:noetnn'''Powerline super module'''nnimport sysnnfrom argparse import ArgumentParsernnimport psutilnnfrom colormath.color_diff import delta_e_cie2000nnfrom powerline.lib.unicode import unnimport tests.vim as vim_modulennfrom tests import TestCasenn.n

Add support for csv filesEquivalent to airline csv Christian Brabandt plugin integration, but uses Pythonnown facilities.nnNote: filetype detection is out of the scope of the powerline responsibilities.n  CSV is supported by powerline, but only as long as filetype detection isn  done by Vim correctly. By default CSV files are neither detected norn  highlighted.nnSome known differences between powerline code and @chrisbra plugin withncorresponding airline integration:nn1. Detection work differently. I cannot say which is better because I have notn   tested it much, but it is definitely different.n2. My variant is able to detect whether there is (no) header. (Of course,n   relying on Python code.) Airline is using a setting. (Both do not allown   manual per-filetype setting.) Of course, user can force either variant (non   headers at all or headers always).n3. My variant makes it possible to configure header output format, includingn   truncating it at 15 characters (the default).n4. CSV plugin does not work with multiline CSV items (in some dialects one cann   use code like `abc;I<CR>am<CR>multiline<CR>string`). See `:h csv-column` onn   how to fix this if possible (will require also changing `<sid>WColumn`n   function because currently it only works with one line).n5. AFAIK Python does not such a thing as u00e2u0080u009cfixed width CSVu00e2u0080u009d. Thus I do not workn   with this, but CSV plugin does. Not sure whether it is different withn   space-separated CSV files though.n

This is not like tmux-1.6: foreground color isn   different from separator color and equal to (0, 102, 153) for some reasonn   (separator has correct color). tmux-1.8 is fine, so are older versionsn   (though tmux-1.6 and tmux-1.7 do not have highlighting for previously activen   window) and my system tmux-1.9a.n2. screen, xterm and some other non-256color terminals both have the same issuen   and make libvterm emit complains like `Unhandled CSI SGR 3231`.n3. screen-256color, xterm-256color and other -256color terminals make libvtermn   emit complains about unhandled escapes to stderr.n4. `st-256color` does not have any of the above problems, but it may be notn   present on the target system because it is installed with x11-terms/st andn   not with sys-libs/ncurses.nnFor the given reasons decision was made: to fix tmux-1.9 tests and not makenlibvterm emit any data to stderr st-256color $TERM should be used, up untilnlibvterm has its own terminfo database entry (if it ever will).
